WHEREAS, his unique personal style, characterized by his signature bow ties—a
tradition he solidified in the 1970s—became a legendary symbol of his warm, approachable,
and scholarly demeanor on campus; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Barefoot demonstrated a rare ability to engage others on equal footing,
instilling in each acquaintance a genuine sense of importance and comfort, as evidenced when
his sponsor, during his postsecondary education, confidently invited him to quail hunt on his
family's farm in Weakley County—an invitation he graciously accepted; and
WHEREAS, even in retirement, Dr. Barefoot has remained a vital pillar of the university
community, most recently championing the construction of "The Ethos Forum," a state-of-the-art
facility for business and engineering, and generously funding the "Joyce Barefoot Lobby" in
loving memory of his wife and Union's fourteenth First Lady; and
WHEREAS, Dr. Barefoot's life has been defined by a deep commitment to faith and
learning, having influenced countless pastors, educators, and leaders who now serve across
Tennessee and around the globe; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we hereby honor and congratulate Dr. Hyran E. Barefoot on the
celebration of his ninety-eighth birthday and extend to him our best wishes for many happy
returns of the day.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
